⭐ PROGRAM 1: Draw a Line
Aim
To write a C++ program to draw a simple straight line using graphics.

Algorithm
Start the program.
Include <graphics.h> and <conio.h>.
Initialize graphics mode using initgraph().
Use the function line(x1, y1, x2, y2) to draw a line.
Wait for key press using getch().
Close graphics mode using closegraph().
Stop the program.

Program
#include <graphics.h>
#include <conio.h>
int main() {
    int gd = DETECT, gm;
    initgraph(&gd, &gm, "");

    line(100, 100, 300, 100);

    getch();
    closegraph();
    return 0;
}

Result
A straight horizontal line is drawn on the graphics window.

⭐ PROGRAM 2: Draw a Rectangle
Aim
To write a C++ program to draw a rectangle using graphics functions.

Algorithm
Start program and initialize graphics mode.
Call rectangle(left, top, right, bottom) function.
Display the output.
Wait for user input.
Close the graphics window.

Program
#include <graphics.h>
#include <conio.h>
int main() {
    int gd = DETECT, gm;
    initgraph(&gd, &gm, "");

    rectangle(100, 100, 300, 200);

    getch();
    closegraph();
    return 0;
}

Result
A rectangle appears on the graphics window.

⭐ PROGRAM 3: Draw a Circle
Aim
To draw a circle using graphics functions in C++.

Algorithm
Initialize graphics mode.
Use circle(x, y, radius) to draw a circle.
Display output.
Close the graphics mode.

Program
#include <graphics.h>
#include <conio.h>
int main() {
    int gd = DETECT, gm;
    initgraph(&gd, &gm, "");

    circle(250, 200, 80);

    getch();
    closegraph();
    return 0;
}

Result
A circle with radius 80 is displayed.

⭐ PROGRAM 4: Draw a Triangle
Aim
To draw a triangle using line graphics primitives.

Algorithm
Initialize graphics mode.
Draw three lines connecting three vertices.
Display output.
Close graphics window.

Program
#include <graphics.h>
#include <conio.h>
int main() {
    int gd = DETECT, gm;
    initgraph(&gd, &gm, "");

    line(150, 100, 100, 200);
    line(150, 100, 200, 200);
    line(100, 200, 200, 200);

    getch();
    closegraph();
    return 0;
}

Result
A triangle is drawn on the screen.

⭐ PROGRAM 5: Filled Circle Using floodfill
Aim
To draw and fill a circle using fill styles in graphics.

Algorithm
Initialize graphics.
Draw a circle.
Set fill style and color.
Apply floodfill(x, y, border_color).
Close the graphics window.

Program
#include <graphics.h>
#include <conio.h>
int main() {
    int gd = DETECT, gm;
    initgraph(&gd, &gm, "");

    circle(250, 200, 80);
    setfillstyle(SOLID_FILL, RED);
    floodfill(250, 200, WHITE);

    getch();
    closegraph();
    return 0;
}

Result
A red filled circle appears on the graphics screen.

⭐ PROGRAM 6: Display Text in Graphics
Aim
To display text inside a graphics window.

Algorithm
Initialize graphics.
Use outtextxy(x, y, text) to print text.
Wait for user input.
Close graphics.

Program
#include <graphics.h>
#include <conio.h>
int main() {
    int gd = DETECT, gm;
    initgraph(&gd, &gm, "");

    outtextxy(100, 100, "Graphics Programming in C++");

    getch();
    closegraph();
    return 0;
}

Result
The message “Graphics Programming in C++” is displayed on the graphics window.

⭐ PROGRAM 7: Draw Pixel Line (Using putpixel)
Aim
To draw a line pixel by pixel using putpixel().

Algorithm
Initialize graphics.
Use loop to plot pixels.
Display output.
Close graphics.

Program
#include <graphics.h>
#include <conio.h>
int main() {
    int gd = DETECT, gm;
    initgraph(&gd, &gm, "");

    for (int i = 100; i <= 300; i++)
        putpixel(i, 200, WHITE);

    getch();
    closegraph();
    return 0;
}

Result
A straight horizontal line is drawn using pixels.

⭐ PROGRAM 8: Smiley Face
Aim
To draw a smiley face using graphics functions.

Algorithm
Start graphics.
Draw circle for the face.
Draw two eyes and an arc for the smile.
Close graphics.

Program
#include <graphics.h>
#include <conio.h>
int main() {
    int gd = DETECT, gm;
    initgraph(&gd, &gm, "");

    circle(250, 200, 100);        // face
    circle(220, 170, 10);        // left eye
    circle(280, 170, 10);        // right eye
    arc(250, 220, 200, 340, 50); // smile

    getch();
    closegraph();
    return 0;
}

Result
A smiley face is displayed in the graphics window.
